), but both species can be separated by their different size (TL = 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.41" metricValueMax="1.46" metricValueMin="1.3599999999999999" pageId="1" pageNumber="420" unit="mm" value="14.1" valueMax="14.6" valueMin="13.6">13.6–14.6 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName authority="Hendrich &amp; Balke, 2020" authorityName="Hendrich &amp; Balke" authorityYear="2020" box="[232,340,1871,1897]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydaticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hauthi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[232,340,1871,1897]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">H. hauthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[347,438,1871,1897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[347,438,1871,1897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="420" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and TL = 13.0–14.0 mm in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Megna, Balke, Apenborn &amp; Hendrich" authorityYear="2019" box="[759,907,1872,1897]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydaticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="panguana">
<emphasis box="[759,907,1872,1897]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">H. panguana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), colour patterns of the elytra (
<figureCitation box="[1260,1373,1871,1897]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[278,1310,179,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[278,1310,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dorsal habitus of H. hauthi sp. nov., holotype, male (a); H. lateralis (b) and H. panguana (c), both from Panguana Research Station, Huanuco Department, Peru. Scale bar = 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3688348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3688348/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">Figs 1a, c</figureCitation>
), and length and shape of the median lobes (
<figureCitation box="[581,654,1907,1933]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–3" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1939,1964]" captionTargetBox="[185,1403,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[185,1403,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–3. Median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal (a) and lateral view (b): H. hauthi sp. nov. (2), H. lateralis (3) and H. panguana (4). The anterior margin of the membranous lateral “wings” of the median lobe in 3b and 4 b have been enhanced digitally for more contrast and better visibility. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3688350" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3688350/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 4). The other larger species in 
<collectingCountry box="[1007,1061,1907,1933]" name="Peru" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">Peru</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Laporte, 1835" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1835" box="[1072,1364,1906,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydaticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lateralis">
<emphasis box="[1072,1199,1907,1933]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">H. lateralis</emphasis>
Laporte, 1835
</taxonomicName>
(TL = 
<quantity box="[151,317,1943,1969]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.335" metricValueMax="1.38" metricValueMin="1.29" pageId="1" pageNumber="420" unit="mm" value="13.35" valueMax="13.8" valueMin="12.9">12.9–13.8 mm</quantity>
), has yellow longitudinal stripes and a subtriangular, postmedial and broad spot on each elytron (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[278,1310,179,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[278,1310,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dorsal habitus of H. hauthi sp. nov., holotype, male (a); H. lateralis (b) and H. panguana (c), both from Panguana Research Station, Huanuco Department, Peru. Scale bar = 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3688348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3688348/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">Fig. 1b</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, the median lobe of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1835" box="[571,698,1979,2005]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydaticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lateralis">
<emphasis box="[571,698,1979,2005]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">H. lateralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much smaller and has a different shape than the median lobe of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hendrich &amp; Balke, 2020" authorityName="Hendrich &amp; Balke" authorityYear="2020" box="[151,257,2015,2041]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydaticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hauthi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,257,2015,2041]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">H. hauthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,354,2015,2041]" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[264,354,2015,2041]" pageId="1" pageNumber="420" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[369,437,2015,2041]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–3" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1939,1964]" captionTargetBox="[185,1403,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[185,1403,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2–3. Median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal (a) and lateral view (b): H. hauthi sp. nov. (2), H. lateralis (3) and H. panguana (4). The anterior margin of the membranous lateral “wings” of the median lobe in 3b and 4 b have been enhanced digitally for more contrast and better visibility. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3688350" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3688350/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="420">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="421" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,153,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is dedicated to our young and keen colleague David Hauth (Marburg, 
<collectingCountry box="[1316,1425,153,179]" name="Germany" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">Germany</collectingCountry>
), specialist for different xylophagous beetle families. The specific epithet is a substantive in the genitive case.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="421" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,153,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,224,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">Distribution.</emphasis>
So far 
<taxonomicName authority="Hendrich &amp; Balke, 2020" authorityName="Hendrich &amp; Balke" authorityYear="2020" box="[437,631,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydaticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hauthi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[437,631,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">Hydaticus hauthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[638,729,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[638,729,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[1010,1058,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">type</typeStatus>
locality in the El Sira Mountains (
<figureCitation box="[159,260,260,288]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–6" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1946,1971]" captionTargetBox="[183,1404,519,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[183,1404,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 5–6. Cloud forest at 1500 m in the Cordillera El Sira, Peru (5) and habitat of Hydaticus hauthi sp. nov. in Peru (6) (Photos by Armin Niessner)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3688352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3688352/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">Figs 5, 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="421" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,153,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,297,323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">Ecology.</emphasis>
All specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hendrich &amp; Balke, 2020" authorityName="Hendrich &amp; Balke" authorityYear="2020" box="[514,710,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydaticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hauthi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[514,710,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">Hydaticus hauthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[719,811,297,323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[719,811,297,323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="421" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
were collected in a partly shaded, shallow, temporary forest pool, rich in decaying leaves (
<figureCitation box="[569,639,333,360]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–6" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1946,1971]" captionTargetBox="[183,1404,519,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[183,1404,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 5–6. Cloud forest at 1500 m in the Cordillera El Sira, Peru (5) and habitat of Hydaticus hauthi sp. nov. in Peru (6) (Photos by Armin Niessner)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3688352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3688352/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="421">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). No other 
<taxonomicName box="[771,891,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Dytiscidae</taxonomicName>
were collected, just a few 
<taxonomicName box="[1201,1313,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Gyrinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Gyrinidae</taxonomicName>
have been observed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
